  "text": "Pro-inflammatory cytokines play a prominent role in classical neuroinflammatory diseases, such as MS and encephalitides. We demonstrated that splenocytes extracted from 5Z-7-oxozeaenoltreated EAE mice display a significant decrease in IL-17A, IFN-γ, TNF-α, and IL-6 production in response to MOG restimulation. In EAE mice model, the BBB is compromised. Immune cells can invade to the CNS through a compromised BBB and vice versa. 5Z-7-oxozeaenol may cross the BBB to exert its effect on splenocytes. Similar results have been described for other methods of TAK1 inhibition. For example, in vivo RNAi-mediated silencing of TAK1 in the mouse significantly decreases IL-17A, IFN-γ, and TNF-α secretion produced by the spleen in collagen-induced arthritis [CITATION_1] . 5Z-7-oxozeaenol also inhibits pro-inflammatory cytokines in the CNS. However, there is some disagreement in regards to the therapeutic time-window of 5Z-7-oxozeaenol for ameliorating the neurological deficit score, EAE pathology and pro-inflammatory cytokine production, which cannot be simply explained by limiting T cell responses or pro-inflammatory cytokines. These incongruences are likely to be explained by the contribution of other cells that contribute to the pathogenesis of EAE, such as microglia.",
